00:08:49.170 --> 00:08:50.190
fluids, fluids, fluids,

283
00:08:50.190 --> 00:08:52.110
you keep flushing the kidneys.

284
00:08:52.110 --> 00:08:54.000
Okay, Compartment Syndrome.

285
00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.620
Compartment Syndrome is the other thing,

286
00:08:55.620 --> 00:08:58.050
injury that can happen to the extremity.

287
00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:00.180
Here you have this crush injury

288
00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:01.110
to an extremity,

289
00:09:01.110 --> 00:09:03.420
the classic is the lower extremity,

290
00:09:03.420 --> 00:09:05.190
but it can be any other extremity,

291
00:09:05.190 --> 00:09:09.570
and when the pressure inside that compartment,

292
00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:11.670
the magic number is greater

293
00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:13.800
than 30 millimeters of mercury,

294
00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:15.900
that's the magic number,

295
00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.750
that's when you should call up a surgeon,

296
00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:19.583
a trauma surgeon,

297
00:09:19.583 --> 00:09:20.970
a vascular surgeon, orthopedic,

298
00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:22.260
whoever's available,

299
00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:24.150
they need to then do their fasciotomy

300
00:09:24.150 --> 00:09:25.983
and open up that compartment.

301
00:09:27.510 --> 00:09:28.530
Environmental injuries,

302
00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:30.630
I'll mention it real quick,

303
00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:31.740
there's heat and cold.

304
00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:32.910
Cold and heat ones,

305
00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:34.170
the cold is real easy,

306
00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:36.240
either a frostnip or frostbite,

307
00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:37.410
the difference between the two

308
00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:38.820
is that frostbite,

309
00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:40.844
there's cellular death,

310
00:09:40.844 --> 00:09:43.620
frostnip, there's no tissue loss.

311
00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:45.474
The treatment for frostbite

312
00:09:45.474 --> 00:09:47.040
is you do rapid rewarming

313
00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.170
in circulating water,

314
00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:50.610
there, you got it.

315
00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.040
Heat, just the opposite,

316
00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:54.510
is the difference between

317
00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:56.700
heat exhaustion and heat stroke.

318
00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.320
Very common, you know,

319
00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:00.690
if I'm sure down here in Texas

320
00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:03.270
you'll see a lot of heat related stuff

321
00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:04.380
coming to your ER

322
00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:05.310
and you'd have to decide

323
00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:06.780
if it's exhaustion,

324
00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:07.980
they'll be sweaty,

325
00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:09.270
they'll feel terrible,

326
00:10:09.270 --> 00:10:10.440
but they're sweating

327
00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.810
and their neuro exam is normal.

328
00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:14.700
Heat stroke,

329
00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.950
you have the temperature greater than 104

330
00:10:16.950 --> 00:10:20.130
and they're having CNS dysfunction.

331
00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:21.247
CNS dysfunction is not,

332
00:10:21.247 --> 00:10:22.860
"I feel terrible and weak",

333
00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:24.450
that's not CNS dysfunction.

334
00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:25.350
They will have,

335
00:10:25.350 --> 00:10:27.240
they will look septic,

336
00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.070
they will have some CNS dysfunction,

337
00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:30.150
they can't speak,

338
00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:31.740
they can't do something, okay?

339
00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:33.900
All right, I wanna move on

340
00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:35.760
to the surgical abdomen now,

341
00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:38.613
that's the last 18 minutes of my talk.

342
00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:40.890
That's the other,

343
00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:41.723
we're gonna go,

344
00:10:41.723 --> 00:10:43.110
we're gonna move into a different area.

345
00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:44.960
I've done the environmental stuff now

346
00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.870
we're now gonna put our surgeon hats on.

347
00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:52.170
All right, so David mentioned

348
00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:55.140
he's gonna cover upper and lower GI later,

349
00:10:55.140 --> 00:10:57.180
those are the non-surgical stuff,

350
00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:59.040
I'm gonna do the surgical stuff

351
00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:01.290
and when it comes to the surgical abdomen,

352
00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:02.370
there's really only two reasons

353
00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:03.810
to call up a surgeon.

354
00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:07.560
One is the patient has acute peritonitis, right?

355
00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:08.640
They have peritonitis

356
00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:10.800
and a surgeon needs to get involved for that

357
00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:12.270
or they're obstructed.

358
00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:13.103
That's it,

359
00:11:13.103 --> 00:11:14.010
those are the two reasons

360
00:11:14.010 --> 00:11:15.720
to call up a surgeon immediately

361
00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:17.280
that you're gonna want them for.

362
00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:18.870
All right, so let's dig into this

363
00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:20.370
a little bit further, of course.

364
00:11:20.370 --> 00:11:22.260
When it comes to peritonitis,

365
00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:24.240
you have spontaneous bacterial peritonitis,

366
00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:25.073
you have secondary

367
00:11:25.073 --> 00:11:26.010
and you got tertiary.

368
00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:29.250
So, the spontaneous peritonitis

369
00:11:29.250 --> 00:11:32.280
doesn't necessarily need a surgeon,

370
00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:34.170
but it does need some antibiotics, all right,

371
00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:36.780
and this happens in your cirrhotic patients,

372
00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:38.070
typically a gram-negative,

373
00:11:38.070 --> 00:11:39.870
E. coli gets in there

374
00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:40.920
and you need to put them on

375
00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:42.540
broad spectrum antibiotics

376
00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:44.610
that covers particularly E. coli.

377
00:11:44.610 --> 00:11:46.680
Secondary peritonitis is what

378
00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:48.150
you and I almost all,

379
00:11:48.150 --> 00:11:49.350
the more common thing.

380
00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:51.000
This is the appendicitis,

381
00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.970
this is the diverticulitis, all right,

382
00:11:53.970 --> 00:11:55.290
and so here you really need

383
00:11:55.290 --> 00:11:56.370
to call up your surgeon

384
00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:58.620
and to have source control.

385
00:11:58.620 --> 00:12:00.720
Get that appendix out,

386
00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:01.890
manage the diverticulitis,

387
00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:02.823
you got the idea,

388
00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:05.970
and then there's tertiary,

389
00:12:05.970 --> 00:12:07.080
which you'll sometimes get

390
00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:09.090
and that is the surgeon took care of,

391
00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:10.620
let's say the appendix,

392
00:12:10.620 --> 00:12:14.177
and oh, they got a post-surgical abcess,

393
00:12:15.517 --> 00:12:17.760
all right, or a post-op infection.

394
00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:20.970
So, those are now more opportunistic infections

395
00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:22.980
and you have to control those.

396
00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:24.240
I will just make in one,

397
00:12:24.240 --> 00:12:26.100
just to distinguish this,

398
00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:27.690
the spontaneous bacterial peritonitis

399
00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:29.970
versus infection

400
00:12:29.970 --> 00:12:31.710
associated with peritoneal dialysis,

401
00:12:31.710 --> 00:12:34.320
just know the diagnosis,

402
00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:36.450
the numbers are just a little different.

403
00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:37.283
You have 250,

404
00:12:37.283 --> 00:12:39.000
greater than 250 white blood cells

405
00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.280
for spontaneous bacterial peritonitis.

406
00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:45.600
Peritoneal dialysis is usually due to gram-positives,

407
00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:47.310
usually staph or strep,

408
00:12:47.310 --> 00:12:49.560
and as soon as you have any suspicion of that

409
00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:50.550
and you have any white cells,

410
00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:52.450
you need to cover for staph and strep.

411
00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:55.560
All right, abdominal pain,

412
00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:56.910
when it comes to the elderly,

413
00:12:56.910 --> 00:12:58.620
be careful,

414
00:12:58.620 --> 00:12:59.700
they often have,

415
00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:01.650
they're often harboring something worse.

416
00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:03.150
They more often get hospitalized,

417
00:13:03.150 --> 00:13:04.320
more likely to be diagnosed,

418
00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:05.910
more likely needed surgery,

419
00:13:05.910 --> 00:13:07.650
so, you know, when I have patients

420
00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:08.760
come in with abdominal pain

421
00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:09.960
and they're elderly

422
00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:12.067
and I'm contemplating,

423
00:13:12.067 --> 00:13:14.790
"Ah, it's constipation",

424
00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:17.197
I just take a step back and say,

425
00:13:17.197 --> 00:13:18.300
"Is it really constipation?

426
00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:19.170
Is it something else?"

427
00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:20.580
I just make certain

428
00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:22.380
before I discharge that patient

429
00:13:22.380 --> 00:13:24.510
with constipation as a cause

430
00:13:24.510 --> 00:13:26.643
of that elderly person's abdominal pain.

431
00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:30.480
All right, let's talk about some specific conditions

432
00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:32.340
they can ask you about

433
00:13:32.340 --> 00:13:34.170
when it comes to the abdomen

434
00:13:34.170 --> 00:13:36.840
and that is abdominal wall and hernias.

435
00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:38.280
So, let's talk about hernias,

436
00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:40.050
I like to work my way in.

437
00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:42.000
So, here's a question,

438
00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.800
you have a 72-year-old female

439
00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:45.390
presents with a six hour history

440
00:13:45.390 --> 00:13:47.760
of painful lump in her groin.

441
00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:49.290
There's some nausea, no vomiting,

442
00:13:49.290 --> 00:13:50.310
no fever, chills,

443
00:13:50.310 --> 00:13:52.290
just a painful lump in the groin.

444
00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:54.120
You go examine the patient,

445
00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:55.560
the abdomen's fine,

446
00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:58.950
the right groin has a palpable mass below

447
00:13:58.950 --> 00:14:01.080
or inferior to the inguinal ligament.

448
00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.340
Despite gentle firm pressure,

449
00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:04.083
the mass does not disappear.

450
00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:06.660
Hmm?

451
00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:08.607
The most likely diagnosis is,

452
00:14:08.607 --> 00:14:11.310
"A, a strangulated indirect inguinal hernia,

453
00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:13.710
B, a reducible direct inguinal hernia,

454
00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:16.110
C, an incarcerated femoral hernia

455
00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:18.837
or D, an incarcerated Spigelian hernia."

456
00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:25.263
All right, so good,

457
00:14:25.263 --> 00:14:26.250
2/3's of you got it,

458
00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:28.680
it's an incarcerated femoral hernia.

459
00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:30.270
Why is it most likely to be

460
00:14:30.270 --> 00:14:32.070
an incarcerated femoral hernia?

461
00:14:32.070 --> 00:14:34.560
Well just recognize the, you know, the difference

462
00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:36.630
between incarcerated and strangulated.

463
00:14:36.630 --> 00:14:37.920
Incarcerated means it's stuck,

464
00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:39.180
you can't reduce it

465
00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:43.140
and when the vascular supply is finally compromised,

466
00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:44.370
now it's strangulated,

467
00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:46.353
that portion of the bowel is dying.

468
00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:50.190
The most common hernias you'll find

469
00:14:50.190 --> 00:14:52.200
are the indirect inguinal hernias,

470
00:14:52.200 --> 00:14:54.480
that's the most common one,

471
00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:56.670
direct is second most common.

472
00:14:56.670 --> 00:14:58.950
When you've got that inguinal hernia,

473
00:14:58.950 --> 00:14:59.783
I love it when the residents

474
00:14:59.783 --> 00:15:01.027
come up and say this to me,

475
00:15:01.027 --> 00:15:02.400
"Oh, well I saw a patient,

476
00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:03.780
they have an indirect inguinal hernia."

477
00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:04.613
I say, "How do you know that?"

478
00:15:04.613 --> 00:15:05.446
"Well, they got a lump there

479
00:15:05.446 --> 00:15:06.279
in the groin right here."

480
00:15:06.279 --> 00:15:08.370
It's like on exam,

481
00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:11.190
you cannot tell if it's indirect or direct,

482
00:15:11.190 --> 00:15:12.023
you can't tell,

483
00:15:12.023 --> 00:15:14.433
you just have the lump there in the groin, okay?

484
00:15:15.420 --> 00:15:16.920
Now the femoral hernias,

485
00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:17.753
right off the bat,

486
00:15:17.753 --> 00:15:18.810
are more common in women

487
00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:20.485
and as I had in that

488
00:15:20.485 --> 00:15:21.318
and said in that question,

489
00:15:21.318 --> 00:15:22.530
it's located below

490
00:15:22.530 --> 00:15:25.350
or inferior to the inguinal ligament,

491
00:15:25.350 --> 00:15:27.663
typically medial to the femoral pulse.

492
00:15:29.670 --> 00:15:31.147
This question comes up sometimes,

493
00:15:31.147 --> 00:15:33.240
"Is watchful waiting appropriate?"

494
00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:34.170
So, you have someone

495
00:15:34.170 --> 00:15:36.633
who's got an inguinal hernia, all right,

496
00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:40.230
they may say, "Doc, do I need

497
00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:41.530
to get this operated on?",

498
00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:43.537
or you might be thinking,

499
00:15:43.537 --> 00:15:45.150
"Should I send 'em to a surgeon?"

500
00:15:45.150 --> 00:15:45.983
Well, this is where you have

501
00:15:45.983 --> 00:15:47.610
shared decision making with the patient.

502
00:15:47.610 --> 00:15:50.430
So, if they've got an inguinal hernia

503
00:15:50.430 --> 00:15:52.680
and it's not bothering them much,

504
00:15:52.680 --> 00:15:53.513
you just happen to pick it up,

505
00:15:53.513 --> 00:15:54.607
"Yep, it's there."

506
00:15:54.607 --> 00:15:55.440
"I didn't even know it,

507
00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.300
you know, just not bothering me."

508
00:15:57.300 --> 00:15:58.980
It's completely reducible

509
00:15:58.980 --> 00:15:59.813
and you know,

510
00:15:59.813 --> 00:16:01.560
"I really don't wanna get an operation",

511
00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:02.730
that's appropriate.

512
00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:05.010
Okay, you can do watchful waiting.

513
00:16:05.010 --> 00:16:06.570
You may wanna counsel 'em on the fact

514
00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:09.090
that the chance of it becoming a surgical emergency

515
00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:10.650
is actually very low.

516
00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:12.720
It actually is very, very low.

517
00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:14.520
However, most patients,

518
00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:15.475
about 3/4's,

519
00:16:15.475 --> 00:16:17.760
2/3's to 3/4's of 'em eventually,

520
00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:19.110
eventually find their way

521
00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:20.010
into the hands of a surgeon

522
00:16:20.010 --> 00:16:22.270
'cause it does end up getting uncomfortable

523
00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:24.847
and they'll ask you this question,

524
00:16:24.847 --> 00:16:27.150
"Well, if I got this thing in my groin,

525
00:16:27.150 --> 00:16:28.410
can I still exercise?

526
00:16:28.410 --> 00:16:29.243
Can I still run?

527
00:16:29.243 --> 00:16:30.076
Can I do stuff?"

528
00:16:30.076 --> 00:16:31.320
The answer is yes.

529
00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:34.590
Remember, exercise is good, okay,

530
00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:37.233
it's always the answer on the Boards, okay.

531
00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:39.293
All right, next question,

532
00:16:39.293 --> 00:16:41.227
this is a true case.

533
00:16:41.227 --> 00:16:42.600
"67-year-old patient with a history

534
00:16:42.600 --> 00:16:44.100
of chronic low back pain

535
00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:45.780
presents with six hours

536
00:16:45.780 --> 00:16:48.960
of sudden, severe, diffuse abdominal pain."

537
00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:51.630
His medications include celecoxib

538
00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:53.550
because of his chronic use for his back pain,

539
00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:56.760
three days ago he went to an orthopedic urgent care

540
00:16:56.760 --> 00:16:58.080
because his back pain worsened

541
00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:00.180
and they put him on a Medrol Dosepak.

542
00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:01.920
His vital signs there, you see,

543
00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:02.753
blood pressure's okay,

544
00:17:02.753 --> 00:17:03.586
he's tacky,

545
00:17:03.586 --> 00:17:04.560
his respiratory rate's up,

546
00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:05.393
oh by the way,

547
00:17:05.393 --> 00:17:07.110
that's SIRS, okay? (chuckling)

548
00:17:07.110 --> 00:17:08.407
He's afebrile,

549
00:17:08.407 --> 00:17:09.810
"his abdomen's diffusely tender,

550
00:17:09.810 --> 00:17:11.190
with guarding and rebound,

551
00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:12.840
an upright chest x-ray demonstrates

552
00:17:12.840 --> 00:17:15.390
free air under the diaphragm."

553
00:17:15.390 --> 00:17:16.223
Hmm?

554
00:17:16.223 --> 00:17:17.056
All right,

555
00:17:18.150 --> 00:17:20.070
the most likely diagnosis in this situation

556
00:17:20.070 --> 00:17:21.600
would be an "acute ischemic bowel,

557
00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:23.340
B, a perforated duodenal ulcer,

558
00:17:23.340 --> 00:17:24.720
C, a perforated appendicitis

559
00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:26.997
or D, a perforated diverticulitis."

560
00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:34.500
Good, perforated duodenal ulcer.

561
00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:35.790
That sounds good to me,

562
00:17:35.790 --> 00:17:36.900
that's exactly what it is.

563
00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:40.620
This person's at high risk for just that, okay,

564
00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:44.100
the perforated duodenal ulcer

565
00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:46.260
is the most common cause

566
00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:47.610
for air under the diaphragm

567
00:17:47.610 --> 00:17:49.650
or free air in the abdomen.

568
00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:51.870
All right, why?

569
00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:53.850
Why was this person at high risk?

570
00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:55.290
They're on chronic NSAID use

571
00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:56.640
and then you put 'em on a steroid

572
00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:57.600
on top of it?

573
00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:59.700
Don't do that. (chuckling)

574
00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:01.200
Don't do that.

575
00:18:01.200 --> 00:18:02.520
Nothing good on the gut

576
00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:04.590
when you do that, all right,

577
00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:06.090
and yes, you can,

578
00:18:06.090 --> 00:18:07.140
if you're in your office setting,

579
00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:08.730
you don't have a CT available,

580
00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:10.350
just do the upright chest x-ray,

581
00:18:10.350 --> 00:18:11.790
it's really, really sensitive.

582
00:18:11.790 --> 00:18:13.890
It's old school I know,

583
00:18:13.890 --> 00:18:15.870
but it does get you an answer

584
00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:17.940
and it can detect very, very little air

585
00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:19.470
under the diaphragm.

586
00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:23.250
Okay, all right, next patient.

587
00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:24.307
Something else in the abdomen.

588
00:18:24.307 --> 00:18:26.550
"A 60-year-old patient presents to the ED",

589
00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:27.870
or your office "with three days

590
00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:29.700
of worsening right upper quadrant pain.

591
00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:31.380
The pain radiates to the right scapula,

592
00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.150
there's nausea and vomiting."

593
00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:34.410
The temperature, hmm,

594
00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:35.243
that's not good,

595
00:18:35.243 --> 00:18:36.076
it's elevated.

596
00:18:36.076 --> 00:18:37.620
Pulse, hmm, elevated,

597
00:18:37.620 --> 00:18:39.240
blood pressure, not too good,

598
00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:40.710
90 over 45.

599
00:18:40.710 --> 00:18:42.150
He and worse than this,

600
00:18:42.150 --> 00:18:44.010
he's jaundiced,

601
00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:45.930
and his bilirubin's 7.8.

602
00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:47.930
His right upper upper quadrant's tender,

603
00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:50.827
most likely diagnosis here is

604
00:18:50.827 --> 00:18:52.470
"A, acute cholecystitis,

605
00:18:52.470 --> 00:18:53.880
B, ascending cholangitis,

606
00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:55.200
C, gallstone pancreatitis

607
00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:57.207
or D, gallstone ileus."

608
00:19:02.010 --> 00:19:03.570
Now hopefully a lot of you picked B.

609
00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:04.800
2/3's of you did, good,

610
00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:07.440
it's ascending cholangitis.

611
00:19:07.440 --> 00:19:10.260
This gentleman is demonstrating Charcot's triad.

612
00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:13.020
Well, let's get into gallstone disease.

613
00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:15.393
So, who's at risk of getting gallstones?

614
00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:18.090
People, well, there's a family history,

615
00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:19.380
that's one,

616
00:19:19.380 --> 00:19:21.090
obesity, sedentary lifestyle,

617
00:19:21.090 --> 00:19:22.890
cyclic weight change.

618
00:19:22.890 --> 00:19:23.907
They have asked this question in the past

619
00:19:23.907 --> 00:19:24.990
and it's true,

620
00:19:24.990 --> 00:19:27.610
patients who have dramatic loss in weight

621
00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:30.770
such as when they go through bariatric surgery

622
00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:33.903
will precipitate out stones.

623
00:19:35.055 --> 00:19:36.630
(chuckling) I've got a funny feeling

624
00:19:36.630 --> 00:19:37.980
I'll start seeing some reports

625
00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:39.720
not too distant future

626
00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:41.400
that when people are taking

627
00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:43.050
the Wegovy's of the world,

628
00:19:43.050 --> 00:19:44.550
that they start, yeah,

629
00:19:44.550 --> 00:19:46.560
'cause everybody's on them now (chuckling) it seems

630
00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:48.450
that they're gonna start precipitating out gallstones,

631
00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:49.283
so be aware,

632
00:19:49.283 --> 00:19:51.903
be careful with cyclic weight change.

633
00:19:53.220 --> 00:19:55.350
It's not always just cholesterol stones,

634
00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:56.183
by the way,

635
00:19:56.183 --> 00:19:57.016
think about patients

636
00:19:57.016 --> 00:19:59.790
who have high red blood cell turnover

637
00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:01.140
such as your sickler's,

638
00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:02.190
they will have black,

639
00:20:02.190 --> 00:20:03.450
the hemoglobin stones

640
00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:06.390
are the black pigmented stones.

641
00:20:06.390 --> 00:20:07.223
All right, but again,

642
00:20:07.223 --> 00:20:08.056
the cholesterol stones

643
00:20:08.056 --> 00:20:10.380
are the most common ones, 80%.

644
00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:13.350
What do you do if the patient is,

645
00:20:13.350 --> 00:20:14.220
oh they went,

646
00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:15.600
they were 65,

647
00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:17.880
they went for their Triple A exam,

648
00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:19.140
like we talked about earlier,

649
00:20:19.140 --> 00:20:20.910
and, oh, the ultrasonographer just decided

650
00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:22.110
to take a look at the right upper quadrant

651
00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:24.060
'cause, well, they just had some time

652
00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:25.443
and they see some stones.

653
00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:27.780
You know, you get the report back,

654
00:20:27.780 --> 00:20:29.040
gallstones,

655
00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:29.873
you ask the patient,

656
00:20:29.873 --> 00:20:30.840
"You got any belly pain,

657
00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:31.687
right upper quadrant pain?"

658
00:20:31.687 --> 00:20:33.150
"No, I don't have any pain."

659
00:20:33.150 --> 00:20:34.890
So, asymptomatic stones,

660
00:20:34.890 --> 00:20:36.510
what do you do with them?

661
00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:38.700
Nothing, (laughing) okay?

662
00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:39.810
Nothing, all right,

663
00:20:39.810 --> 00:20:40.980
you do not do anything

664
00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:42.450
'cause the vast majority of 'em

665
00:20:42.450 --> 00:20:44.610
will have no problem with them.

666
00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:47.340
Once they become symptomatic,

667
00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:49.920
now you're gonna wanna consider surgery.

668
00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:53.460
All right, so how do they present symptomatically?

669
00:20:53.460 --> 00:20:54.840
All right, I like to do things

670
00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:56.520
anatomically in my brain,

671
00:20:56.520 --> 00:20:58.110
so you can have a stone

672
00:20:58.110 --> 00:20:59.310
sitting there in the gallbladder,

673
00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:00.480
you eat the fatty meal,

674
00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:01.650
it kicks around,

675
00:21:01.650 --> 00:21:03.570
you get right upper quadrant pain

676
00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:06.750
and that's biliary colic, right?

677
00:21:06.750 --> 00:21:08.190
When a stone decides to sit there

678
00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:09.660
in the cystic duct,

679
00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:11.490
now it's obstructive

680
00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:13.040
and so what will happen is that

681
00:21:14.310 --> 00:21:16.050
the bile will start backing up behind it,

682
00:21:16.050 --> 00:21:17.190
it will get infected,

683
00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:18.750
typically with a gram-negative,

684
00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:21.900
you'll then get some right upper quadrant pain

685
00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:23.190
and discomfort.

686
00:21:23.190 --> 00:21:25.950
You'll have a positive Murphy's sign, right,

687
00:21:25.950 --> 00:21:27.390
and positive Murphy's sign,

688
00:21:27.390 --> 00:21:28.223
by the way,

689
00:21:28.223 --> 00:21:29.056
I always ask the residents this,

690
00:21:29.056 --> 00:21:30.600
they always get it wrong,

691
00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.460
is you have the patient laying down,

692
00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:34.290
you put your hand in the right upper quadrant,

693
00:21:34.290 --> 00:21:35.550
deep in there

694
00:21:35.550 --> 00:21:37.680
and it's not ouch at that point,

695
00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:38.640
that's a Murphy's sign,

696
00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:40.470
it's you take a deep inspiration,

697
00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:41.580
ah-ah-ah, ah, (inhaling)

698
00:21:41.580 --> 00:21:44.520
and it's cessation with inspiration

699
00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:46.170
is a positive Murphy's sign.

700
00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:48.270
Okay, cessation of inspiration.

701
00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.970
All right, now let's say the stone

702
00:21:50.970 --> 00:21:53.700
decides to get into the common duct,

703
00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:55.830
now that was our case scenario,

704
00:21:55.830 --> 00:21:56.880
you're gonna end up potentially

705
00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:58.247
with ascending cholangitis

706
00:21:58.247 --> 00:22:01.470
'cause now you've got that common duct obstructed,

707
00:22:01.470 --> 00:22:02.670
it will dilate,

708
00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:05.610
bile will back up into the liver,

709
00:22:05.610 --> 00:22:07.080
you get jaundiced,

710
00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:09.060
you have right upper quadrant pain,

711
00:22:09.060 --> 00:22:10.380
you'll typically get fever,

712
00:22:10.380 --> 00:22:13.050
again from gram-negatives infecting the area,

713
00:22:13.050 --> 00:22:14.610
that's Charcot's triad,

714
00:22:14.610 --> 00:22:15.570
that was our patient,

715
00:22:15.570 --> 00:22:17.190
ascending cholangitis.

716
00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:18.780
Sometimes the stone decides to go down

717
00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:20.130
and obstruct the ampulla of Vater,

718
00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:22.050
that's gallstone pancreatitis,

719
00:22:22.050 --> 00:22:23.190
and last but not least,

720
00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:26.730
sometimes that you get a huge, huge stone

721
00:22:26.730 --> 00:22:27.840
that will erode through

722
00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:29.200
the wall of the gallbladder

723
00:22:30.551 --> 00:22:31.830
and create a fistula

724
00:22:31.830 --> 00:22:34.500
and it will enter the small bowel

725
00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:36.810
and it will then travel downtown

726
00:22:36.810 --> 00:22:37.980
and then get hung up

727
00:22:37.980 --> 00:22:39.360
at the most narrow portion,

728
00:22:39.360 --> 00:22:40.980
the ileocecal valve,

729
00:22:40.980 --> 00:22:43.890
and then you will get a gallstone ileus,

730
00:22:43.890 --> 00:22:46.320
that's what gallstone ileus is.

731
00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:48.540
All right, everything I just told you

732
00:22:48.540 --> 00:22:50.130
is on this slide.

733
00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:51.270
You can just take this slide out,

734
00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:52.530
it's exactly what I just told you

735
00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:53.940
or you can look at the pretty pictures,

736
00:22:53.940 --> 00:22:55.908
whichever way you best remember it,

737
00:22:55.908 --> 00:22:57.540
(chuckling) all right.

738
00:22:57.540 --> 00:22:59.280
All right, how do you go about evaluating patients?

739
00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:01.748
A patient comes in with some right upper quadrant pain,

740
00:23:01.748 --> 00:23:02.910
you know, you say, "Well,

741
00:23:02.910 --> 00:23:04.470
sounds like gallstone disease."

742
00:23:04.470 --> 00:23:06.720
All right, so you start with an ultrasound.

743
00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:08.700
Suppose you're convinced

744
00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:11.160
it sure sounds like biliary colic,

745
00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:14.430
it sure sounds like gallstone disease,

746
00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:16.890
but there's no stone there.

747
00:23:16.890 --> 00:23:20.100
Well, they may have the functional gallbladder disorder.

748
00:23:20.100 --> 00:23:22.470
It used to be what we call dyskinesia,

749
00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:23.400
but the fancy term is

750
00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:25.530
the functional gallbladder disorder.

751
00:23:25.530 --> 00:23:26.700
So, in those situations,

752
00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:29.580
you send them on for a nuclear scan,

753
00:23:29.580 --> 00:23:30.600
whether you call it a PIPIDA

754
00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:31.433
or a HIDA scan,

755
00:23:31.433 --> 00:23:33.540
whatever your place calls it,

756
00:23:33.540 --> 00:23:37.200
and if they have a a decreased ejection fraction

757
00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:39.480
that's abnormal.

758
00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:40.313
Those patients,

759
00:23:40.313 --> 00:23:42.390
if they go on for their cholecystectomy,

760
00:23:42.390 --> 00:23:45.000
in general, will do well

761
00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.583
for their functional gallbladder disorder.

762
00:23:48.960 --> 00:23:50.370
All right, I'm moving from the right upper quadrant

763
00:23:50.370 --> 00:23:51.330
to the right lower quadrant,

764
00:23:51.330 --> 00:23:53.130
appendicitis.

765
00:23:53.130 --> 00:23:55.740
Very common, as you can see,

766
00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:57.300
6% to 7% of the population

767
00:23:57.300 --> 00:23:58.133
at one point in time

768
00:23:58.133 --> 00:23:59.490
will have appendicitis,

769
00:23:59.490 --> 00:24:00.603
it's often due to an appendicolith

770
00:24:00.603 --> 00:24:02.280
that gets lodged in there

771
00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:04.410
and everything behind that appendicolith

772
00:24:04.410 --> 00:24:06.870
gets dilated, infected

773
00:24:06.870 --> 00:24:08.640
and you have appendicitis.

774
00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:11.010
There's some of the number of the signs there,

775
00:24:11.010 --> 00:24:12.120
I will mention,

776
00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:13.650
and why I put in red down below,

777
00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:18.650
the Carnett sign is not a sign of appendicitis.

778
00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:21.120
They've asked this question,

779
00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:23.790
Carnett sign is when you ask the patient

780
00:24:23.790 --> 00:24:27.210
to do an abdominal crunch, okay,

781
00:24:27.210 --> 00:24:29.610
and if the pain persists with the crunch

782
00:24:29.610 --> 00:24:31.710
or it's still tender with a crunch,

783
00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:32.543
when you're crunching,

784
00:24:32.543 --> 00:24:33.450
what are you doing?

785
00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:36.330
You're protecting the peritoneum, right?

786
00:24:36.330 --> 00:24:37.530
So, all you're doing

787
00:24:37.530 --> 00:24:39.420
is getting abdominal wall

788
00:24:39.420 --> 00:24:41.550
origin of that pain, okay,

789
00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:43.110
not inside.

790
00:24:43.110 --> 00:24:44.400
The others are the ones

791
00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:47.790
associated with appendicitis, however,

792
00:24:47.790 --> 00:24:48.623
Rovsing's sign,

793
00:24:48.623 --> 00:24:50.370
Psoas sign, obturator sign,

794
00:24:50.370 --> 00:24:51.210
this is the signs

795
00:24:51.210 --> 00:24:52.920
and how you do them.

796
00:24:52.920 --> 00:24:54.813
All right, so here's a question,

797
00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:57.090
You have a 6-year-old,

798
00:24:57.090 --> 00:24:58.327
you're evaluating for abdominal pain,

799
00:24:58.327 --> 00:24:59.760
"You have a moderate degree of suspicion

800
00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:01.080
that the patient has appendicitis."

801
00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:02.580
He's tender over McBurney's point,

802
00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:03.413
it hurts down there, right,

803
00:25:03.413 --> 00:25:04.246
lower quadrant,

804
00:25:04.246 --> 00:25:05.141
he's not eating,

805
00:25:05.141 --> 00:25:05.974
he may even be vomiting.

806
00:25:05.974 --> 00:25:07.020
"The American College of Radiology

807
00:25:07.020 --> 00:25:08.460
and American Academy of Pediatric recommends

808
00:25:08.460 --> 00:25:09.377
which of the following

809
00:25:09.377 --> 00:25:10.210
as the first choice

810
00:25:10.210 --> 00:25:11.250
to evaluate this patient?"

811
00:25:11.250 --> 00:25:13.590
You should start with an X-ray of the abdomen,

812
00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:15.060
you should start with an abdominal ultrasound,

813
00:25:15.060 --> 00:25:15.990
you should start with a CT

814
00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:16.823
of the abdomen and pelvis

815
00:25:16.823 --> 00:25:17.790
or you should start with an MRI

816
00:25:17.790 --> 00:25:19.260
of the abdomen and pelvis.

817
00:25:19.260 --> 00:25:21.600
What are you gonna send this child for

818
00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:23.520
to help firm up your diagnosis

819
00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:25.203
before you call the surgeon?

820
00:25:29.970 --> 00:25:30.803
All right, good,

821
00:25:30.803 --> 00:25:31.636
hopefully you got this.

822
00:25:31.636 --> 00:25:32.640
Yeah, you start with ultrasound,

823
00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:34.050
everybody's gotten familiar with this now.

824
00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:34.883
You do ultrasound,

825
00:25:34.883 --> 00:25:36.990
yes, ultrasound is really, really useful

826
00:25:36.990 --> 00:25:38.170
in this age group

827
00:25:39.210 --> 00:25:41.790
as well as in patients under the age 14

828
00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:43.530
or if they're pregnant, okay,

829
00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:44.940
that's what you go with,

830
00:25:44.940 --> 00:25:47.200
otherwise in adults you start with CT

831
00:25:48.377 --> 00:25:50.970
and they're non-pregnant, all right?

832
00:25:50.970 --> 00:25:53.550
All right, now there was one question,

833
00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:54.450
in-service question,

834
00:25:54.450 --> 00:25:56.160
and so I put this in

835
00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:57.990
and you may ask me in the Q &amp; A,

836
00:25:57.990 --> 00:25:59.430
so I just, I put this in.

837
00:25:59.430 --> 00:26:00.360
Could it show up with the Boards?

838
00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:01.410
I don't know,

839
00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:02.670
but it's this whole idea

840
00:26:02.670 --> 00:26:06.180
of maybe we don't need to send everybody off

